{"schema_version":1,"event_id":"evt_e901915b-632c-4e73-9dce-b6b2425b4c0d","event_type":"review_disposition","recorded_at":"2026-07-23T19:30:41.715Z","operator_workflow":"skill-evolution","target":{"name":"grilling","repo_relative_path":".claude/skills/grilling","content_hash":"314a80595a7bea1d80679e2bc73a17ab3ef492729e8750bb31ee73877063dfc8","repo_head":"8e3cca85bca97ef77e3709dc0adddeafe76fc3fd"},"top_level_session_id":"1d5c9424-a0b7-4af4-af2b-587bca65d419","payload":{"review_id":"rev_7b300394-8acb-4ed6-9cc5-556562a45a8e","disposition":"candidate_rejected_validation","adjudicated_event_ids":["evt_37651b29-7ada-4390-94bd-cf439d03af16"],"note":"Mechanism: intake verb 'load' for a named supporting skill can be satisfied by a file read instead of a real invocation. Blind comparative validation (5 paired trials, 22 executor samples, 11/version) showed the current 'load' wording did NOT reproduce the file-read shortcut on any fresh reproduction case (3/3 current-version executors invoked via the Skill tool), and the candidate ('invoke ... run the skill itself, not a file read') produced zero behavioral separation and no regression across all trials. Candidate not materially better (and +20 words larger) -> acceptance gate fails, live skill left unchanged. Original incident appears load-induced in a multi-step run the isolated probe cannot replicate; a genuine recurrence must reopen eligibility with new evidence."}}
